07453nam a22007575i 9780822397977DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223979777 a10.1515/97808223979772doi  a(DE-B1597)552676  a(OCoLC)1229161120  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aQ175.55b.S294 1996 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aRoss, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScience Wars /cAndrew Ross. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tScience Is "Good to Think With" -- tDoes Science Put an End to History. or History to Science? Or. Why Being Pro-science Is Harder than You Think -- tMeeting Polemics with Irenics in the Science Wars -- tMy Enemy's Enemy Is-Only Perhaps - My Friend -- tThe Gloves Come Off: Shattered Alliances in Science and Technology Studies -- tThe Science Wars: Responses to a Marriage Failed -- tWhat Is Science Studies for and Who Cares? -- tUnity. Dyads. Triads. Quads. and Complexity: Cultural Choreographies of Science -- tMaking Transparencies: Seeing through the Science Wars -- tGender and Genitals: Constructs of Sex and Gender -- tTen Propositions on Science and Antiscience -- tDispatches from the Science Wars -- tThe Politics of the Science Wars -- tConsolidating the Canon -- tDetoxifying the "Poison Pen Effect" -- tThe Flight from Reason: Higher Superstition and the Refutation of Science Studies -- tA la recherche du temps perdu: A Review Essay -- tScience Skirmishes and Science Policy Research -- tA Few Good Species -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the highly fractious Culture Wars, conservatives in science have launched a backlash against feminist, multiculturalist, and social critics in science studies. Paul Gross and Norman Levitt's book Higher Superstition, presented as a wake-up call to scientists unaware of the dangers posed by the "science-bashers," set the shrill tone of this reaction and led to the appearance of a growing number of scare stories about an "antiscience" movement in the op-ed sections of newspapers across the country. Unwilling to be political scapegoats for the decline in the public funding of science and the erosion of the public authority of scientists, many of these critics-natural scientists, sociologists, anthropologists, historians, and scholars in cultural studies and literary studies-have taken the opportunity to respond to the backlash in Science Wars.At a time when scientific knowledge is systematically whisked out of the domain of education and converted into private capital, the essays in this volume are sharply critical of the conservative defense of a value-free science. They suggest that in a world steeped in nuclear, biogenic, and chemical overdevelopment, those who are skeptical of technology are more than entitled to ask for evidence of rationality in those versions of scientific progress that respond only to the managerial needs of state, corporate, and military elites. Whether uncovering the gender-laden assumptions built into the Western scientific method, redefining the scientific claim to objectivity, showing the relationship between science's empirical worldview and that of mercantile capitalism, or showing how the powerful language of science exercises its daily cultural authority in our society, the essays in Science Wars announce their own powerful message. Analyzing the antidemocratic tendencies within science and its institutions, they insist on a more accountable relationship between scientists and the communities and environments affected by their research.Revised and expanded from a recent issue of Social Text, Science Wars will provoke thought and controversy among scholars and general readers interested in science studies and current cultural politics.Contributors. Stanley Aronowitz, Sarah Franklin, Steve Fuller, Sandra Harding, Roger Hart, N. Katherine Hayles, Ruth Hubbard, Joel Kovel, Les Levidow, George Levine, Richard Levins, Richard C. Lewontin, Michael Lynch, Emily Martin, Dorothy Nelkin, Hilary Rose, Andrew Ross, Sharon Traweek, Langdon Winner  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aScience and state. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aRoss, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelkin, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovel, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinner, Langdon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevidow, Les, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLynch, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayles, N. Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewontin, Richard C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevins, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbard, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r